{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_calhoun_ver01/data/sn83016244/00513689925/1958041701/0522.xml":{"full_text":"THE KBY WIST CITIZEN Thursday, April 17, 1956\nPage 6\nThe Key West Citizen\nPubUshed Sunday Morning and Every Week Day Afternoon,\nExcept Saturday\nMltor\nAdvertising Manarar\nCirculation Manager\n\u00bbrT R mw K nv KRTa Mechanical Superintendent\nMEMBER OF ASSOCIATED PRESS\nCatered at Ke* West, Florida aa\nSecond Class Matter\nCARRIER SUBSCRIPTION RATES\nTear\n6 Months 1 1\n1 Month 1\n1 Week \"\".v..\nMAIL RATES\n1 Year\nMonths 1\nM T 11?\n(No weekly mall subscriptions Accepted)\nNATIONAL ADVERTISING REPRESENTATIVES: J\nTHEIS SIMPSON, CO., INC.\n1 B. 54th St.. New York M. N. Y.\nBranch Offlcee In Principal Cities\nThose Bridge Fishermen:\nAsking For A Casket\nPerhaps someday somebody will be able to explain\nto us why people go on asking for death by fishing from\nthe bridges on U. S. 1.\nThe county and state have spent thousands of dol\nlars to build special catwalks out of the way of traffic\nfor bridge fishermen. Some bridge fishermen have been\nkilled. Others have been injured. Others have lost bait,\ntackle and even their pants to speeding cars that missed\nthem by an inch. But they\u2019re still out there, those bridge\nfishermen, hanging out over the highway and almost\ndaring drivers to hit them.\nIs there a law against such fishing?\nIf there is, it\u2019s not very well enforced.\nBetween the road construction crews who\u2019ve nar\nrowed parts of the highway to one-lane traffic, the\nbridge fishermen, the drawbridges and a few slow-mo\ntion drivers, U. S. 1 is becoming more like an obstacle\ncourse than anything else.\nThe road crews, though, are there to do a job\u2014\nthat\u2019s a necessary thing. The slow-motion drivers\u2014\nwell, tourists do like to slow up and look around. And\nboats have to use the channels under the drawbridges.\nBut those bridge fishermen don\u2019t have to fish from the\nhighway, and we wish they\u2019d quit!\nMaybe they don\u2019t worry about themselves.\nIf not, they sure do worry everybody else.\nOn a recent trip to Miami, we counted exactly 34\nof these death-defying sportsmen clinging to the rail\n-1 Ings between here and Islamorada. For the most part,\n.they were standing well out into the lane of traffic, and\nonly leaning on the horn sent them up against the rail\nings. With a heavy truck in one lane, us in the other\nand the fishermen on each side, it was a pretty crowded\nbridge and if any of us had so much as twitched, some\nof us wouldn\u2019t be around to read this editorial.\nThe worst of it is that in most'courts, the driver\nwho hits a pedestrian of any kind has two strikes against\nhim. Juries tend to sympathize with the mah on foot,\nrather than the man behind the wheel. That\u2019s one\nreason liability insurance rates are so high. In a close\nsqueak it isn\u2019t always the bridge fisherman at fault\nwho gets killed. It may be some innocent people who\nswerved just a few inches too far toward the opposite\nlane of traffic to keep from hitting him. Precision driv\ning is tough on a highway where cars move 60 miles\nan hour.\nWhy don\u2019t these people use the catwalks?\nThat\u2019s what they were built for!\nWe\u2019ve heard them claim that the catwalks weren\u2019t\nbuilt \u201cwhere the fish are.\u2019\u2019 Oh yes? Some of pur of\nfending bridge fishermen were fishing not ten feet from\na catwalk s end. Fish don\u2019t stay in one spot without\nmoving very long away. Do tourists think the catwalks\nare unsafe? We can assure them they\u2019re safe or Mon\nroe County wouldn\u2019t encourage their use if they weren\u2019t.\nWe wish the fishermen would stay on them. None of us\nenjoys looking at the bloody mess that results, every\nnow and theii, when some fisherman doesn\u2019t use those\ncatwalks put there for his own enjoyment and for every\nbody\u2019s safety*. j\n\nFor Harder Education\nA great many Americans seem to have a passion\nfor neat, positive answers. When it comes to tactual\ndata the tallest building, the longest bridge, the big\ngest dam such answers are possible. The trouble is\nthat a lot of people think they can also get such answers\nto questions of quite a different sort.\nThey want to know: What is the most beautiful\nbuilding? They ask: Which is the best painting in the\nworld? They say: We want to know who are the hap\npiest people on earth. There are no clear-cut answers\nto questions like that. This is disturbing to some people.\nIt is disturbing to them, too, when there is hesitation\nabout answering another question: Whose educational\n\u2022yatem is the best?\nJ\nThat question has been asked persistently in recent\nmonths. The only possible reply is another question:\nBest for what purpose? Even when that has been de\nfined, no simple, definite answer is possible.\n*lt is eminently clear, however, that our educational\nsystem is not all that we would like it* to be. Despite\nthe defensive tactics of teachers, college deans and\neducational professors, the conviction is spreading\namong thoughtful people that, much of the nation\u2019s high\nschool training is too easy, that most students should\nhave more \u201chard\u201d education more mathematics,\nscience, languages.\nThe recent Gallup poll taken among more than 1,000\nhigh school principals reflects this feeling. It is most\nstriking that 79 per cent of these principals thought the\nschools demanded .too little work from students, and\nthat 63 per cent of them thought students were not re\nquired to read enough books. This is not the final an\nswer; none is possible. But it is well worth thinking\nabout.\ni 1\nTanylast\nWORDS, UONEW A\n(HELPP\nt A I MISS\nc \u00b0vnty V, AF\n7 \u2014lll 1 11\nZx F h\na i wmW 1 -a\u2014 ill\nAI Iff 1 h;\nCZ Ulf\nVilli I I\u2019\nlull n\nDll y\u2019\nIt\u2019s $15,000,000,000 Off 1957 Boom Level\nU.S. Production Rate Falls\nBy STERLING F. GREEN\nWASHINGTON W*\u2014Government\nofficials estimated today the na\ntion\u2019s production rate has fallen\nabout 15 billion dollars a year be\nlow the boom level of six months\nago.\nThe Commerce Department\u2019s\nestimate of total national output,\nsoon to be released, reportedly\nwill show that the 71i-biUion-dol\nlar skid in the last quarter of 1957\nwas approximately equaled by the\nfprther drop in first-quarter 1958.\nThe report will bolster the evi\ndence that the recession already\nis deeper than that of 1953-4, in\nformants said, and in several re\nspects is matching the sharper\nslump of 1949-50.\n\u2022The trends last month still were\ndownward. The fall was less rap\nid, and this has stiffened the re\nsistance of key administration ad\nvisers to quick antirecession rem\nedies\u2014a general tax cut or mas\nsive public works.\nSome officials contend they see\nsigns that the bottom is near.\nThe forthcoming Commerce De\npartment report, officials said\nprivately, will show that the\n\u201cgross national product\u201d the\nvalue of all goods and services\nproduced\u2014has dipped to an an\nnual rate of roughly 425 billion\ndollars or less.\nThis is a bit more than 3 per\ncent below last summer's 440-bil\nlion-dollar rate. It was a trifle\ngreater than the percentage de\ncline from top to bottom of the\n1953-54 recession. It matches the\nmore severe 1949-50 decline when\nthat recession was half a year\nold.\nGovernment economists are\nstudying an unusual series of\ncharts prepared by the privately\nsupported Committee for Econom\nic Development, a nonprofit eco\nnomic research organization of\nbusinessmen. It proposes a* tem\nporary, across-the-board, 20 per\ncent cut in income taxhs to boost\npublic purchasing power.\nCrossword Puzzle\n83. Think of\n35. Biblical\ncharacter\n28. Low\neverahoe\n28. Breathe\n40. PWrioda\nof time\n44. Henry\u2019s\neon\n48. Talon\n47. Diminish\n50. Command\n52. So. Amer,\nanimal\n53. Stowe\ncharacter\n54. Distant:\nprefix\n55. Reviles\n56. Atmospheric\nmoisture\n571 Building\naddition\nACROSS\n1. Summit\n4. Footlike\nP**\n7. Leaven\n12. Philippine\nmt\n13. High:\nmusical\n14. Anxious\n15. Genus of\nfreah-water\nsnails\n17. Floor\n18. Of an age\n19. Marble\n21. Ancient\nPeraian coin\n23. Close of\nday\n27. Large\nvulture\n29. Female\ndeer\n30. Placid\nSo far the present recession has\nbeen as sharp, in many respects,\nas that of 1949-50. To CED's re\nsearch staff it seems doubtful that\nan uptrend will be as early or as\npronounced. Some buoyant ele\nments are missing. Housing starts\nwhich were rising in 1949-50, are\nnow depressed. Government\nspending was rising steeply' in\n1949-50, but is moving up very\ngradually this year. Retail sales\nwere still rising in 1949-50; they\nare declining now. And prices\ndropped in 1949-50; today their\nsteady climb is discouraging con\nsumer demand.\nOn the other band, the personal\nincome of Americans has held up\nmuch better in the past six months\nthan it did in 1949-50 (but not so\nwell as in 1953-54). This presum\nably is because of improved un\nemployment compensation and so\ncial security benefits, more em-\nGirl Scouts Together\nBrownie Troop 60 meets at the\nLutheran Church every Friday af\nternoon. We have divided our\ntroop into three patrols named\nOrchids, Perriwinkles and the Pas\nsions. Mrs. Orvis Kemp is our\nleader and Mrs. John Schacht and\nMrs. John Hess are the co-lead\ners.\nWe started the year with the\nfollowing former Brownies: Susan\nBade, Pam James, Seeth Mika,\nDonna Moss, Karen Myers, Patty\nGrotto, Karen Kemp, Jacklyn Sch\nact, Anny Torry, and Linda Thom\npson. All of the above have earn\ned their year pins. Susan Bacle\nand Karen Myers have earned\ntheir second year star.\nDuring the year we invested\nSydall Dallmeyer, Terry Pateet,\nBrooksie Schacklesworth, Susan\nClaugh, Pam Hess, Barbie Gei\nger, Merrie Glennon, Fem Ham\nilton, Rosemary Ischar and Jean\nette Rozanski into our troop. We\nall enjoyed the investiture cere-\n|a|c|e|sMs|h|old\u00bba|cltl\nBd|a|v|i IdlMt|i |n|t|s]\nSaffian\n|r| i |v|a|lMm|a|t|e.|SM\nlolp e r a t eidlmm i lle.l\n|p|e|nb\u00df m \u00b0tfMd o e r|\n|e|s|tMdly|e|dMs|n|a|&|\n\u2022elution of Yesterday's Puzzle\n\u2022.Portrayed\ndramatically\n7. Day before\ntoday\n9. Devoured\n9. Gone by\n10. E> Indian\nweight\n11. Attempt\n16. Carroll\nheroine\n20. Keep away\nfrom\n22. Deems\n24. Cretan\nmountain\n25. Negative\n26. Turn right\n28. Approaches\n90. Knight's\ntitlo\n31. Prior in\ntime\n21 Oriental\ncommander\n34. Choose\n37. Required\n39. Small: law\n\u2018A. Winged\n41 Badgerlike\nanimal\n43. Enlarge\n45. Reside\n47. Corroded\n48. Poor\n49. Himalayan\nmountain\nIL Crow's note\nDOWN\n1. Domesti\ncated\n2. Music\ndrama\n2. Arctic\n4 Dairy\nutensil\n5. Lamb\u2019s\npen name\nployec-paid supplemental benefits,\nand other cushions. Many more\njobless men have some income\nwho would have been on relief 10\nyears ago.\nSome economists have found\nmore reason for pessimism than\nfor optimism in the CED findings.\nThis is largely because of the ab\nsence of some upward forces that\nformerly prevailed. There is ex\ncess capacity in vital industries\nand export demand is declining.\nBut there are signs of a coming\npick-up in home building; defense\nspending should rise, and some\nimportant industries are finally\ngetting their excess inventories\nwork'd off.\nFamily \u201eicome remains not far\nbelow th? peak levels of last sum\nmer. Economists hope the con-\nsumer, who has been saving at a\nhigh rate, may soon decide to re\nsume spending with confidence.\nmony when we heard the Brown\nie Story while seated around the\nmirror decorated with leaves and\nflowers to represent the pool in\nthe story. On this special occa\nsion we were served brownies\nand punch.\nWanda Strickland transferred to\nour troop from another local troop\nand Laurina Moore transferred\nfom a troop in Kodiak, Alaska.\nLaurina brought the Brownie scrap\nbook she had made and we were\nall intered to see the things the\nBrownies did in Alaska.\nThis year we made a field trip\nto the beach where we hunted\nshells and we took a hike and\nlearned to lay and follow trails.\nWe wifi always remember our trip\nto Summerland Key on Juliette\nLowe\u2019s birthday and especially\nour trip to the Turtle Kraals where\nthe monkey wanted to be a Brown\nie and stole Rosemary's beanie.\nAt Christmas time we made\ncenterpieces from coconuts. We\npainted faces on them and dressed\nthem as Santas with red caps\nand cotton beards. We had a spec\nial Christmas party in the evening\nand invited our parents and bro\nthers and sisters to join in the\nfun.\nValentine\u2019s day we had our\ntroop\u2019s birthday party with a large\ndecorated birthday cake. We made\nplacemats for the party by weav\ning strips of red and white paper.\nMrs. W. A. Miller, Girl Scout\nCouncil President was our guest.\nAt Easter we made baskets from\nfrozen pie tins and filled them\n\u25a0with grass and a rabbit we made\nfrom a boiled egg.\nWe learned many new songs\nand games this year. We es\npecially enjoyed the visit Mrs.\nNeil Saunders made to our troop\nand the songs and games she\ntaught us.\nWe have five Fly-ups in our\ntroop who are working on their\nTenderfoot. We all enjoy learning\nsome of the requirements with\nthem. Our mothers appreciated\nour learning the \u201ccorrect\u201d way to\nset the table.\nWe have ail enjoyed being\nBrownies this year and are look\ning forward to many more years\nof scouting fun.\n_ 1\nSam Rayburn Will Run\nSHERMAN, Tex. in House\nSpeyer Sam Rayburn has given\nformal notice he\u2019ll run for a 24th\nterm in Congress. County Demo\ncratic Chairman R. C. Slagle said\nRayburn, 76, filed for a place on\nthe ballot in the party\u2019s July pri\nmary while he was back for an\nEaster visit at his Bonham, Tex.,\nhome.\nHal Boyle Says\nNEW YORK (fl\u2014For* the first\ntime in the postwar world, Joe\nCollege may not find people\nstanding in line to offer him Jobs\nwhen he says farewell to the\ncampus this June.\nWhat does a young graduate\nneed to get ahead in a business\nrecession?\n\u201cFirst of all, he needs to find\nhimself,\u2019\u2019 said Arthur Rubloff of\nChicago, board chairman of one\nof the nation\u2019s largest real estate\ndevelopment firms.\n\u201cFailure to find themselves is\nwhat defeats most young men.\nYou have to go out and find your,\nself. Nobody win find you for you.\n\u201cA man should like his work.\nHe\u2019s a sucker to stay for long at\nit otherwise. But if he doesn\u2019t\nknow what he wants to do, then\nhe certainly will end up having\nto do something he doesn't want.\u2019*\nRubloff at 55 has supervised\nbuilding projects totaling more\nthan half a billion doUars. He\nwent to work in a laundry at the\nage of 9, quit school at 12.\nHe sold newspapers, shined\nshoes, set pins in a bowling alley,\nworked as a galley boy and deck\nhand on Great Lakes freighters.\nHe then went into the real estate\nfield at 17\u2014and earned $7,000 in\ncommissions his first year.\nUnlike many self made men,\nhowever, Rubloff is a firm advo\ncate of education.\n\u201cIt has never been more funda\nmental to business, or more im\nportant to success,\u2019\u2019 he says,\n\u201cbecause the world is becoming\nmore specialized.\u2019\u2019\nHe also believes college gradu\nates are wrong to feel that the\npresent recession is any great or\npermanent barrier to advance\nment.\n\u201cSome young people seem to\nfeel that the days of great op\nportunities are past,\" he said.\n\u201cNothing could be farther from\nthe truth. The opportunities today\nare greater than they ever have\nbeen in the history of mankind.\n\u201cEven with this so-called reces\nsion, there are more $70,000 to\n$lOO,OOO jobs open than there ever\nwere. The corporations are weed\ning out their second best men,\nand looking for top talent and\nthey\u2019ll pay any price for it.\u201d\nNaturally, corporations aren\u2019t\noffering jobs like this to a man\njust out of college. How does he\nclimb to that rank?\n\u201cIt isn\u2019t merely a matter of\nPopulation\nIncrease Off\nWASHINGTON (fl The month\nto-month increase in the nation\u2019s\npopulation was.less in February\nthan in any month in the past five\nyears.\nCensus Bureau statisticians said\ntoday the February slump was\ncaused by an increase in deaths\nbecause of respiratory ailments in\ncluding the second wave of Asian\nflu.\nHere\u2019s what the bureau figures\nhappened to the civilian popula\ntion in February:\nFor the first time since Feb\nruary 1953, the month-to-month\ngain did not top 200,000; the civil\nian population increased by 195,-\n000 to a total of 170,562,000.\nWith the armed forces added,\nthe estimated population on March\n1 was 173,210,000, representing a\nFebruary gain of 199,000. Here\nagain the increase was at a five\nyear low.\nThe Census Bureau says its esti\nmates could be off by a few\nthousand one way or the other.\nIt said there were 10,000 more\ndeaths-in February than in the\nsame month a year ago, and 5,000\nfewer births.\nAbout 10,000 Hungarian refugees\nentered the country in February\n1957.\nHEAR WITH\nBOTH EARS!\nB Shown It\nTransistor;\ninvented\nend made\npossible by\nBell Telephone Laboratories\nEntirely Cordless\nWorn In Ear\nEar Level Hearing\nFully Automatic\no No Buttons or Controls to\nConfuse You\no Needs No Tubes\nFREE\nBOOKLET\nMall Coupon to\nDahlberg\nHEARING SERVICE\nc/o K.W. Citizen\nBox 214-A\nr n\nCHECK YOU* OWN HEABINO\nSlight IOM\nCan hear but not understand\nQ Severe loaa\na Gentlemen: Please send me FREE\nBOOKLET on \"Mlracle Ear\" to\nplain cover. No obligation. g\ng Name g\ng Address g\naty\neither genius or hard work alone,\u2019\u2019\nsaid Rubloff. \u201cIt\u2019s easy to tell\nsomebody to work hard.\n\u201cI think a young man does need\n90 per cent energy to go with the\n10 per cent judgment he has now.\nAnd I feel that if he uses his\nenergy sensibly, it will he>p him\nmature in judgment.\n\u201cBut just working hard isn\u2019t\nthe main thing. The basic things\nare to have a real desire to suc\nceed, a pride in accomplishment,\nand to think in terms of how you\ncan help the other fellow.\n\u201cBut there is a bell of a lot\nmore to success than working\nhard. Laborers work hard.\n\u201cMy guess is that only one out\nof 100 people really wants to\nachieve. The rest just seem lost.\nThey wait for something to hap\npen to them. But nothing is going\nto happen to them.\u201d\nHere are Rubloff\u2019s other prac\ntical tips:\n\u201cOrganize yourself.\n\u201cBe well-liked. You do this by\nbeing fair.\n\u201cTake an active' part in com\nmunity programs. This will give\nyou a rounded conception of\nhuman relations you can get in\nno other way. And understanding\nhuman relations is vital today.\nThe well-liked man who under\nstands people, gets along better\nthan the smarter man who isn't\nliked.\n\u201cIf you have persistence and\nlike people, don\u2019t worry at your\nlack of genius. If every one of\nthe 63 million workers in America\nwas a genius, this country would\nbe in a hell of a mess.\n\u201cFinally, always give ae much\nor more than you get, and never\nlose faith in human nature. Be\ncause one man has done you\nwrong, don\u2019t turn your ear from\nthe next fellow.\u201d\nTHE KEY WEST CITIZEN\nRadio and Television Listings\nCHANNEL 4 TV WTVJ\nTBUBBDAI BVBNTNO\nS:U Sports 8:30 Shower Stars\n\u00ab:33 Weather 8:30 Playhouse 80*\n6:30 Renick 11:00 News\n6:43 News 11:10 Weather\n7:00 Lone Ranger 11: IS Sports\n7:30 Whirlybirds 11:30 Movie\n8:00 It. Diamond* 1:88 Sign OH\nFBIDAY MOBNINO\nl:U Early Show 8:J0 Playbouae\n7:M News. W'ther 10:00 How You Rate\n8:00 C Kangaroo 11:00 A. Godfrey\n1 11:30 notto*\nFRIDAY AFTERNOON\nU:00 Noon Edition 8:30 Houseparty*\n12:13 Secret Storm 3:00 Bls Payoff*\n13:30 Search 3:30 Verdiet*\n13:45 Quid Light* 4:00 Play\n1:00 Sdsie 4:30 Edge. Night*\n1:30 World Tiirns 5:00 Popeye Play\n8:00 Beat Clock* 8:45 Set Flctloe\nCHANNEL 6 TV HAVANA\nTHURSDAY EVENING\n6:00 Jose Antonio 8:15 Revista\nAlonso Deportiva Esso\n6:56 Fiesta de las 8:30 Pepe Biendl\nSiete Menos 8:00 Hueves de\nCinco Partagas\n7:25 El Album 18:00 Amar ea\nPhillips Vivlr\n7:43 Noticiero 10:30 Anto la\nCMQ-TV Press\n7:59 Los Uos 11:00 Notictoro\nPopa CMQ-TV\nFRIDAY MORNING\n8:00 Patron de I 11:00 LI Coclna\nPruebas CMQ\n111:28 Mediodia\nPoray Studio\nHOURS: t\n10:00 A.M. to 7 P.M.\n404 SOUTHARD STREET\nPHONE CY 6-3088\nCHANNEL 7 TV WCKT\nTHURSDAY EVENINO\n6:30 News, Wther 8:30 Tenn. Ernie\n6:45 NBC News 10:00 R. Clooney\n7:00 26 Men 10:30 Jue Wyman*\n7:30 Tic Tae D\u2019sh* 11:00 News\n8:00 Groucho Man 11:15 Sports\n8:30 Dracnet* 11:80 Jack Paar*\n3:00 Peo. Choice*\nFRIDAY MORNING\n8:53 Market 8:30 Today*\n7:00 Today* 8:55 News\n7:25 News 8:00 Romper Room\n7:20 Today* 18:00 Story A Dsy\n7:55 News 10:30 Treas. Hunt*\n8:00 Today* 11:00 Price. Right*\n8:25 New? 11:30 Truth. Cons.*\nCHANNEL 10 TV .WPST-TV\nTHURSDAY EVENING\n8:00 Dooley Show 0:30 Real McCoys\n6:25 Fishing 9:00 Pst Boone\n6:30 News 9:30 Navy Log*\n6:45 Sports 10:00 Make Me\n6:55 Weather 10:30 Law Says\n7:00 TV Digest 11:00 News\n7:30 Circus Boy 11:10 Sports\n8:00 Zorro 11:20 Theatre\nFRIDAY MORNING\n8:30 News 111:15 Movie\n9:80 Chapel 10:15 Theatre\n8:45 aty Farmer 11:30 Trouble Fr.\n18:00 Newt I\nFRIDAY AFTERNOON\n12:00 Margie 3:00 Bandstand\n12:10 \u00dcberace 3:30 Trust Wife\n2:00 Talk Of Town 4:00 Bandstand\n2:30 Margie 5:00 Buccaneers\n5:30 Mickey Mouse\nWKWF RADIO\nTHURSDAY EVENINO\n8:00 News 8:00 Scotland Yd.\n8:15 Serenada 9:25 News\n6:20 Weather 9:10 Sports\n8:15 Serenade 8:15 Theatre*\n7:00 Ed Morgaa* 10:00 Musle\n7:15 Dinner Dato 11:00 News\n7:10 G Heattor* 11:15 Music\n7:15 Music 12:00 Sigs OH\n7:45 Fulton Lewis*\n8:00 Serenade\nFRIDAY MORNING\n8:80 Early Newa 8:00 World News*\n6:05 Mus. Clock B<ls Mus. Clock\n7:00 News 9:00 Breakfast C.*\n7:05 Mus. Clock 10:00 Morning Med\n7:20 Treas. Chest 10:15 Woman's W\u2019ld\n7:45 Weather 10:10 Melodies\n7:50 March Time 11:00 News\n7:55 News 11:15 Kato Smith*\n11:30 News\n11:35 Queen*\nBROADCASTING\nDiroct from Our Office\nSutro Bros Co.\nMemb. ew York Stock Exchange\n5:05 P.M.\nCLOSING QUOTATIONS\nWKWF\nKey West\nIn Days Gone By\nApril 17, 193$\nSunday, Ne Paper\n\nApril 17, 194$\nAbout 1,000 Shriners and their\nwives took Key West by storm\ntoday. The Shriners, from the\nsouth Florida mainland, held a\nparade through the gaily decorat\ned streets of this city.\nPeter J. Ross announced today\nthat a new lodge of Elks had\nbeen formed at Homestead. Ross\nis district deputy grand exalted\nruler of the Elks. The Elks lodge\nhas about 60 members.\nIron ore production in Venezue\nla topped eleven million tons in\n1956, almost five times the 1950\ntotal.\nGarbage Cans\nand Buckets\nSTRUNK\nLUMBER YARD\n120 SIMONTON STREET\nPHONE CY 6-9091\nThe ONLY Authorized\nFRIGIDAIRE\nAPPLIANCE DEALER\nIN KEY WEST\n1024 DUVAL STREET]\nMARTINEZ\nRefrigerator Co.\nCall CY 6-2942\ne Genuine GM Parti\ne Factory-Trained Service\nI\nFBIDAT AFTEBNOON\n13:3* El Cafe de ia 1:43 Notleiere\nEaqulna CMQ-TV\n1:00 Cuba \u00ab1 Dia 1:00 Patroa de\n1:30 Per Cuba I Pruebaa\nFORMICA\nand Plastic\nWALL TILE\nHEADQUARTERS\nKey West\nFloor Covering\n112 DUVAL STREET\nPHONE CY 6-2512\nFBIDAT AFTEKNOON\n13:00 Tie Tae Cab- I 1:30 Kitty Forte*\n13:30 C*ld Bo You- 3:00 Matinee*\n1:00 Movie I 4:00 Queen\n3:33 Newa, W*ther' 4:45 Romaneee*\n5:00 Movie T\nDrink.\nPIERCE\nBROTHERS\n628 FLEMING\nPHILCO\nFactory-Supervised\nService\nMon. Sot., 9 A.M. S:3O P.M.\nCY 6-5922 CY 6-8511\nKey West 1600\nFBIBAT AFTEBNOON\ns ,rTe r ,:M n\nu:l5 Brownlie 3:00 Melodic\nWeather 3:30 Top 2J*\ni? m u ew Newt*\nS:M MeMlee\nWKWF\ni6oo\nON YOUR DIAL\nFor Quality\nPrinting\nThe Artman Press\nCITIZEN BLDG, CY 6-5661","height":"29129","width":"21043"}}
